        <p>
          ðŸ”¸ Generally, if the lengths of the two sides and an included angle of a triangle are given, then the area of the triangle is <m>\text{A} = \frac{1}{2}\textbf{ab}\textbf{sin}\theta</m>. Where <m>\textbf{ b } \text{is the base and } \textbf{ h }  \text{ height.}</m>
        </p>
       
        <exploration>
            <statement>
                <p>
                     <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               Deriving the Formula: <m>\frac {1}{2}ab\, sin C </m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                           Step 1:   Let's recall the Basic Formula for finding area of a triangle.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                         Area = <m>\frac {1}{2} \times \text {Base} \times \text {Height}</m> 
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>  
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m>\textbf {Step 2: Consider a Triangle with an Angle}</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                           Let's take a triangle ABC with sides <m>a </m>, <m>b </m> and included angle <m>C</m>.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                         Side<m> a</m> and Side <m>b</m> form the triangle.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            The height (h) is perpendicular from the top vertex to the base.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>    
                            </p>    
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\textbf {Step 3: Express Height in Terms of Sin}</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                           Using trigonometry, we know that in a right-angled triangle:
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>\text{sin(Angle)} = \frac{\text{Hypotenuse}}{\text{Opposite}}</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            In our case, the height h is the <m>\textbf{opposite side}</m> of angle C, and side b is the <m>\textbf{hypotenuse}</m>.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                         So, we can write it as:
                                        </p>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>\text{h} = \text{b sin C}</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf {Step 4: Substitute into the Area Formula}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Now, take the basic Formula for finding area of a triangle;
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Substituting <m>\textbf{Base}</m> and <m>\textbf{Height}  = \text{b sin C} </m> .
                                    <md>
                                      <mrow> \text{Area} =\amp \frac {1}{2} \times a \times \text{(b sin C)}</mrow>
                                      <mrow> \text{Area} = \amp  \frac {1}{2} ab \, \text{ sin C}</mrow>
                                    
                                      </md>  
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m> \textbf{NOTE:}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <md>
                                           <mrow> \text{Area} = \amp  \frac {1}{2} ab \, \text{ sin C}</mrow>
                                        </md>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        This formula is useful when we know two sides of a triangle and the angle between them instead of the height..
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    </ol>    

                </p>
            </statement>
        </exploration>
